    2. Exercise intensity:

     b. General ward stay: Out of bed as
  tolerated, sitting warm-ups, standing warm-ups, walking in-room, walking 5-10
  min in hall, walking up one flight of stairs, etc
    2. Exercise intensity: 
     a. To tolerance if asymptomatic
     b. RPE ≦ 13 on a scale of 6–20
     c. HRrest + 20 bpm and HR ≦ 120 bpm as the arbitrary upper
  limit
    3. Exercise duration:
     a. Begin with intermittent bouts
  lasting 3 to 5 minutes as tolerated
     b. Rest period may be a slower walk
  (or complete rest, at the patient’s discretion) that is shorter than the
  duration of the exercise bout. Attempt to achieve a 2:1 exercise/rest
  ratio
    4. Stop exercise training if occurrence of the following adverse
  responses:
     a. Diastolic blood pressure (DBP)≧110 mm Hg
     b. Decrease in systolic blood
  pressure (SBP)≧10 mm
  Hg during exercise
     c. Significant ventricular or atrial
  dysrhythmias with or without associated signs/symptoms
     d. Second- or third-degree heart
  block
     e. Signs/symptoms of exercise
  intolerance, including angina, marked dyspnea, and electrocardiogram (ECG)
  changes suggestive of ischemia
    
    
    
    
    [Rehabilitation Goals]
    1. Limit the deleterious physiological and psychological effects of bed
  rest and CVD.
    2. Enable the patient to safely return to activities of daily living within
  limits imposed by CVD.

  lasting 3 to 5 minutes as tolerated
     b. Rest period may be a slower walk
  (or complete rest, at the patient’s discretion) that is shorter than the
  duration of the exercise bout. Attempt to achieve a 2:1 exercise/rest
  ratio

  responses:

     b. Decrease in systolic blood
  pressure (SBP)≧10 mm
  Hg during exercise
     c. Significant ventricular or atrial
  dysrhythmias with or without associated signs/symptoms
     d. Second- or third-degree heart
  block
     e. Signs/symptoms of exercise
  intolerance, including angina, marked dyspnea, and electrocardiogram (ECG)
  changes suggestive of ischemia
    
    
    
    
    [Rehabilitation Goals]
    1. Limit the deleterious physiological and psychological effects of bed
  rest and CVD.
    2. Enable the patient to safely return to activities of daily living within
  limits imposed by CVD.

data.v:
This is a 73-year-old woman with
  
    [Diagnosis]
    # Acute kidney injury on chronic kidney disease, favor gastrointestinal
  bleeding related
    # GI bleeding (EGD: Gastric ulcers, Forrest III)
    # Normocytic Anemia, suspect GI bleeding or CKD related
    # Bilateral pulmonary edema, cause to be determined
    # Chronic Kidney Disease, Stage 5 (eGFR ~7)
    # Chronic Hepatitis C (Anti-HCV Reactive)
    # L3 compression fractures (2025/11 CT)
    
    [Summary] 
    2025/11–12 Body weight gain about 10kg in 2 months. 
    2026/01/16 Nausea and vomiting episodes noted. 
    2026/01/19 ER visit for exacerbated dyspnea (moving-related), general
  weakness, and productive cough with thick sputum.
    PE: Bilateral coarse breathing sound with wheezing and stridor; bilateral
  lower limbs pitting edema (2+ to 3+).
    Imaging: CXR showed bilateral pulmonary edema.
    Lab: Stool occult blood (2+); elevated renal and liver function.
    Management: Admitted; IV PPI and blood transfusion administered; Diuretics
  given for edema. 
    2026/01/20 EGD performed: Gastric ulcers (Forrest III) in the antrum and
  body. Cardiac echo showed no obvious decrease in LVEF. 
    2026/01/21–02/02 Labs show persistent severe renal impairment (Creatinine
  ~6.0) and fluctuating Hemoglobin (7.8 to 10.6) despite transfusion.
    
    We are consulted for bilateral lower limbs weakness and back pain.
